# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ibm-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The IBM Cloud platform combines infrastructure and platform services into a single environment accessible through the IBM Cloud console, CLI, APIs, and infrastructure‑as‑code tools.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud is used to deploy and manage applications, data, and services across public cloud regions, on‑premises environments, and other cloud platforms.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud represents a strategic approach to cloud computing that prioritizes enterprise-grade reliability, security, and customization.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] It is engineered for organizations with complex regulatory requirements, legacy system integration needs, and mission-critical workloads.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud supports hybrid cloud and multi-cloud deployment models, which enables organizations to run and manage workloads across public cloud, private cloud, on-premises environments, and other cloud platforms from different providers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] This approach is commonly used by enterprises seeking flexibility in workload placement while maintaining centralized governance and security controls.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud integrates with container orchestration management technologies such as Red Hat OpenShift, allowing applications to be deployed and operated consistently across heterogenous environments include multiple public clouds and on-premises infrastructure.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] This model supports applications portability and reduces dependency on a single cloud provider.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform is frequently used in industries with regulatory and operational requirements, such as financial services, healthcare, and government, where hybrid and multi-cloud architectures and employed to address data residency, compliance, and risk management considerations.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] As of 2026, IBM states that its cloud infrastructure spans more than 60 data centers across 19 countries and six multizone regions.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform is organized into regions and availability zones designed to provide fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Each availability zone is an isolated physical location within a region with independent power, cooling, and networking infrastructure.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud provides a range of security and compliance services designed to support enterprise, government, and regulated-industry workloads.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform incorporates Identity and access management, encryption services, confidential computing capability, and network security controls to help organizations protect applications and data across hybrid and multi-cloud environments.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud supports industry compliance standards and certifications including ISO 27001, SOC 2, HIPPA, HITRUST, PCI DSS, FedRAMP, MeitY, and GDPR-related controls.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform has emphasized zero trust security principles and the use of hardware-based security technologies, including confidential computing solutions developed in collaboration with IBM Research.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Security features are integrated across IBM Cloud infrastructure, Kubernetes services, AI platforms, and storage offerings to address cybersecurity, privacy, and data sovereignty requirements.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Through its acquisition of Red Hat, IBM positions OpenShift as a central layer for deploying and managing applications consistently across environments.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] This approach allows enterprises to avoid vendor lock-in by using Open source technologies, maintain workloads across multiple cloud providers, and gradually modernize legacy applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud offers a fully managed Red Hat OpenShift service that automates the deployment and ongoing management of OpenShift clusters.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The service provides several key lifecycle management features.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud handles automated provisioning and updates for the OpenShift configuration and underlying infrastructure including operating system security patches.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud provides a suite of over 190 products and services, focusing on hybrid cloud, AI and security.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Key offerings include Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud for Kubernetes, IBM watsonx, IBM Cloud Paks for containerized software and secure infrastructure like Bare-metal servers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform supports enterprise workloads across financial services and other industries with a focus on compliance and security.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud has been positioned as a platform focused on containers and microservices through its support of open-source technologies such as Kubernetes and Red Hat OpenShift.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud's history traces back to early virtualization efforts in the 1970s and 1980s , but it emerged as a formal, comprehensive cloud service provider in the late 2000s, driven by investments in private cloud and the acquisition of SoftLayer.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The strategy shifted significantly toward hybrid cloud in the late 2010s, solidified by the acquisition of Red Hat.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] SoftLayer had bare-metal compute offerings before other large cloud providers such as Amazon Web Services.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] SoftLayer has hosted workloads for companies such as The Hartford, WhatsApp, Whirlpool, Daimler, and Macy's.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] By April 2015, Bluemix included a suite of over 100 cloud-based development tools "including social, mobile, security, analytics, database, and IoT (internet of things).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Bluemix had grown to 83,000 users in India with growth of approximately 10,000 users each month.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] A year after announcement, Bluemix had made little headway in the cloud-computing platform space relative to its competition, and remained substantially behind market leaders Microsoft Azure and Amazon AWS.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] By August 2016, little had changed in market acceptance of the Bluemix offering.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In February 2016, IBM Bluemix includes IBM's Function as a Service (FaaS) system, or Serverless computing offering, that is built using open source from the Apache OpenWhisk incubator project largely credited to IBM for seeding.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] This system, equivalent to Amazon Lambda, Microsoft Azure Functions, Oracle Cloud Fn or Google Cloud Functions, allows calling of a specific function in response to an event without requiring any resource management from the developer.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In May 2017 IBM released Kubernetes support as the IBM Bluemix Container Service, later renamed to the IBM Cloud Kubernetes Service (IKS).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IKS was built using the open source Kubernetes project.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] This system, equivalent to Amazon Web Services EKS, Microsoft Azure AKS, or Google Cloud GKE, aims to provide a platform for automating deployment, scaling, and operations of application containers across clusters of hosts.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In October 2017, IBM announced that they would rebrand their cloud as IBM Cloud brand, merging all components, thus retiring the Bluemix and Softlayer brands.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In March 2018, IBM launched an industry first managed Kubernetes service on bare metal.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In October 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat, Inc for approximately $34 billion representing IBM's largest acquisition in its history.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The acquisition was completed in July 2019.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In August 2019, 3 weeks after the close of Red Hat acquisition, IBM launched a managed Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM stated the acquisition would position the company as "the world's #1 hybrid cloud provider" by combining Red Hat's open source technologies, including Red Hat Enterprise Linux and OpenShift with IBM's existing cloud infrastructure.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The Red Hat acquisition shaped IBM's cloud strategy, with the company focusing on hybrid cloud solutions that allow enterprises to run workloads across on-premises infrastructure, private clouds, and multiple public cloud platforms.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In May 2026, IBM announced the Red Hat OpenShift Virtualization Service on IBM Cloud, a managed virtualization offering designed to run virtual machines on Red Hat OpenShift deployed on IBM Cloud infrastructure.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The service is built on Red Hat OpenShift Virtualization technologies including KubeVirt and the KVM hypervisor, and is delivered as an IBM-managed service on IBM Cloud VPC bare metal servers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The offering was positioned to address enterprise demand for alternatives to legacy virtualization platforms, emphasizing operational stability, security, compliance, and predictable costs while allowing organizations to maintain a virtual-machine first approach.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM stated that the service is intended to provide a long-term path toward containerization and cloud-native application modernization without requiring immediate architectural changes.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In November 2019, IBM has announced that it had designed the world's first financial services-ready public cloud and that Bank of America was its first committed collaborator and anchor customer, joined shortly thereafter in 2020 by BNP Paribas as its first European anchor client.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM announced in April 2021 the general availability of IBM Cloud for Financial Services, including support for Red Hat OpenShift and other cloud-native technologies.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In July 2021, it was announced that SAP is onboarding two of its finance and data management solutions to IBM Cloud for Financial Services.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In September 2021, it was CaixaBank's turn to boost digital capabilities with IBM Cloud for Financial Services and onboarding to new IBM Cloud Multizone Region in Spain.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud has been adopted by organizations operating in regular and data-intensive including financial services, healthcare, telecommunications, and government.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The platform is often associated with enterprise, hybrid-cloud, and compliance focused workloads, particularly those requiring compliance, data sovereignty and integration with on-premises systems and Red Hat OpenShift environments.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM has held long‑term technology partnerships with organizations in sports and entertainment, where cloud computing, data management, and analytics platforms support large‑scale digital experiences for global audiences.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In 2019, IBM partnered with the USTA to provide new AI-powered tools for the US Open.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In May 2020, IBM announced agreements with six European companies, including Osram and Crédit Mutuel, that use IBM Cloud to access advanced technologies such as AI, blockchain and analytics.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM has also collaborated with The Masters Tournament, the annual golf championship held at Augusta National Golf Club, to support digital experiences for the event.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The partnership spans several decades and includes cloud‑based systems used to manage tournament data and deliver content through the Masters website and mobile applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In motorsport, IBM has entered into a multi‑year partnership with Scuderia Ferrari, under which IBM provides cloud, data, and analytics technologies that support Ferrari’s digital platforms and fan‑facing applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] The collaboration is focused on enhancing digital engagement through cloud‑based services.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM Cloud continued to be considered a leader in bare-metal in 2020, and distinguished itself by providing over 11 million possible custom configurations with the latest Power, Intel, and AMD CPUs and Nvidia GPUs.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] IBM has been reviewed on Gartner Peer Insights where it is assessed by enterprise users in the Strategic Cloud Platform Services category.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] Reviews reflect a range of experiences across industries and use cases, including hybrid cloud deployments and enterprise application workloads.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm-cloud-computing] In 2021, IBM announced it would achieve net zero greenhouse gas emissions by 2030, and has introduced tools such as the IBM Cloud Carbon Calculator to help customers measure and manage the environmental impact of their cloud workloads.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM was founded in 1911 as the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR), a holding company of manufacturers of record-keeping and measuring systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It was renamed "International Business Machines" in 1924 and soon became the leading manufacturer of punch-card tabulating systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] During the 1960s and 1970s, the IBM mainframe, exemplified by the System/360 and its successors, was the world's dominant computing platform, with the company producing 80 percent of computers in the U.S. and 70 percent of computers worldwide.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Embracing both business and scientific computing, System/360 was the first family of computers designed to cover a complete range of applications from small to large.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in 1981 with the IBM Personal Computer; its architecture remains the basis for the majority of personal computers sold today.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company later also found success in the laptop space with the ThinkPad.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Since the 1990s, IBM has concentrated on computer services, software, supercomputers, and scientific research; it sold its microcomputer division to Lenovo in 2005.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM continues to develop mainframes, and its supercomputers have consistently ranked among the most powerful in the world in the 21st century.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company has made inroads in advanced computer chips, quantum computing, artificial intelligence, and data infrastructure.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM employees and alumni have won various recognitions for their scientific research and inventions, including six Nobel Prizes and six Turing Awards.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM originated with several technological innovations developed and commercialized in the late 19th century.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Pitrap patented the computing scale in 1885; Alexander Dey invented the dial recorder (1888); Herman Hollerith patented the Electric Tabulating Machine (1889); and Willard Bundy invented a time clock to record workers' arrival and departure times on a paper tape (1889).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On June 16, 1911, their four companies were amalgamated in New York State by Charles Ranlett Flint forming a fifth company, the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR) based in Endicott, New York.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The five companies had 1,300 employees and offices and plants in Endicott and Binghamton, New York; Dayton, Ohio; Detroit, Michigan; Washington, D.C.; and Toronto, Canada.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Collectively, the companies manufactured a wide array of machinery for sale and lease, ranging from commercial scales and industrial time recorders, meat and cheese slicers, to tabulators and punched cards.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson, Sr., fired from the National Cash Register Company (NCR) by John Henry Patterson, called on Flint and, in 1914, was offered a position at CTR.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson joined CTR as general manager and then, 11 months later, was made President when antitrust cases relating to his time at NCR were resolved.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Having learned Patterson's pioneering business practices, Watson proceeded to put the stamp of NCR onto CTR's companies.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] He implemented sales conventions, "generous sales incentives, a focus on customer service, an insistence on well-groomed, dark-suited salesmen and had an evangelical fervor for instilling company pride and loyalty in every worker".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] His favorite slogan, "THINK", became a mantra for each company's employees.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] During Watson's first four years, revenues reached $9 million ($167 million today) and the company's operations expanded to Europe, South America, Asia and Australia.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson never liked the clumsy hyphenated name "Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company" and chose to replace it with the more expansive title "International Business Machines" which had previously been used as the name of CTR's Canadian Division; the name was changed on February 14, 1924.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] By 1933, most of the subsidiaries had been merged into one company, IBM.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The Nazis made extensive use of Hollerith punch card and alphabetical accounting equipment and IBM's majority-owned German subsidiary, Deutsche Hollerith Maschinen GmbH (Dehomag), supplied this equipment from the early 1930s.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] This equipment was critical to Nazi efforts to categorize citizens of both Germany and other nations that fell under Nazi control through ongoing censuses.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] These census data were used to facilitate the round-up of Jews and other targeted groups, and to catalog their movements through the machinery of the Holocaust, including internment in the concentration camps.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Edwin Black contends in *IBM and the Holocaust* that IBM's dealings with Nazis through its New York City headquarters persisted during World War II.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Nazi concentration camps operated a Hollerith department called Hollerith Abteilung, which had IBM machines, including calculating and sorting machines.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM as a military contractor produced 6% of the M1 Carbine rifles used in World War II, about 346,500 of them, between August 1943 and May 1944.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM built the Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator, an electromechanical computer, during World War II.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It offered its first commercial stored-program computer, the vacuum tube based IBM 701, in 1952.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The IBM 305 RAMAC introduced the hard disk drive in 1956.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company switched to transistorized designs with the 7000 and 1400 series, beginning in 1958.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The 1400 series was the first to deploy over 10000 units, making it its most successful computer device at the time.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1956, the company demonstrated the first practical example of artificial intelligence when Arthur L.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Samuel of IBM's Poughkeepsie, New York, laboratory programmed an IBM 704 not merely to play checkers but "learn" from its own experience.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1957, the FORTRAN scientific programming language was announced.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1961, IBM developed the SABRE reservation system for American Airlines and introduced the highly successful Selectric typewriter.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Also in 1961, IBM used the IBM 7094 to generate the first song sung completely by a computer using synthesizers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The song was Daisy Bell (Bicycle Built for Two).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The recording is now in the United States National Recording Registry.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1963, IBM employees and computers helped NASA track the orbital flights of the Mercury astronauts.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] A year later, it moved its corporate headquarters from New York City to Armonk, New York.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The latter half of the 1960s saw IBM continue its support of space exploration, participating in the 1965 Gemini flights, 1966 Saturn flights, and 1969 lunar mission.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM also developed and manufactured the Saturn V's Instrument Unit and Apollo spacecraft guidance computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On April 7, 1964, IBM launched the first computer system family, the IBM System/360.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It spanned the complete range of commercial and scientific applications from large to small, allowing companies for the first time to upgrade to models with greater computing capability without having to rewrite their applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It was followed by the IBM System/370 in 1970.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Together the 360 and 370 made the IBM mainframe the dominant mainframe computer and the dominant computing platform in the industry throughout this period and into the early 1980s.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] They and the operating systems that ran on them such as OS/VS1 and MVS, and the middleware built on top of those such as the CICS transaction processing monitor, had a near-monopoly-level market share and became the thing IBM was most known for during this period.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Shortly after, IBM unbundled its software and services in what many observers believed was a direct result of the lawsuit, creating a competitive market for software.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1982, the Department of Justice dropped the case as "without merit".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Also in 1969, IBM engineer Forrest Parry invented the magnetic stripe card that would become ubiquitous for credit/debit/ATM cards, driver's licenses, rapid transit cards and a multitude of other identity and access control applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM pioneered the manufacture of these cards, and for most of the 1970s, the data processing systems and software for such applications ran exclusively on IBM computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Laurer developed the Universal Product Code.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM and the World Bank first introduced financial swaps to the public in 1981, when it entered into a swap agreement.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In the early 1970s, the Examination Department of the South Vietnamese Ministry of Education contracted with IBM to computerize all examination records, from registration and application forms to certificates of admission and necessary statistical data.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] By 1974, all subjects in the South Vietnamese high school graduation exam were converted to multiple-choice questions.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Answer sheets for the multiple-choice exams were ordered from the United States, and candidates' papers were graded using an IBM 1230 machine.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The graded papers were then transferred to an IBM 534 machine for punching.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] These punched sheets were then fed into an IBM 360 machine to read the scores, multiply by coefficients, add up the scores, calculate the average score, standard deviation, convert raw scores to standardized scores, and calculate the admission ranking.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The sample group and norm group were carefully selected according to statistical methods to calculate the average score and standard deviation.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in the 1980s with the IBM Personal Computer (IBM 5150).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The computer, which spawned a long line of successors, had a profound influence on the development of the personal computer market and became one of IBM's best selling products of all time.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The PC was not well protected by intellectual property laws.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] As a consequence, IBM quickly began losing its market dominance to emerging, compatible competitors in the PC market.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Experts debate whether this was an early example of successful adoption of open architecture, or a lack of business foresight by IBM.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1985, IBM collaborated with Microsoft to develop a new operating system, which was released as OS/2.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Following a dispute, Microsoft severed the collaboration and IBM continued development of OS/2 on its own but it failed in the marketplace against Microsoft's Windows during the mid-1990s.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1991, IBM began spinning off its many divisions into autonomous subsidiaries (so-called "Baby Blues") in an attempt to make the company more manageable and to streamline IBM by having other investors finance those companies.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Lexmark was acquired by Clayton & Dubilier in a leveraged buyout shortly after its formation.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1997, Deep Blue, a chess computer created by IBM beat Chess World Champion at the time, Garry Kasparov in a six round match following standard tournament rules.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In September 1992, IBM finished spinning off its various microcomputer personal computer manufacturing divisions and were consolidated into an autonomous wholly owned subsidiary known as the IBM Personal Computer Company (IBM PC Co.).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] This corporate restructuring came after IBM reported a sharp drop in profit margins during the second quarter of fiscal year 1992; market analysts attributed the drop to a fierce price war in the personal computer market over the summer of 1992.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The corporate restructuring was one of the largest and most expensive in history up to that point.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM PC Co. introduced the ThinkPad clone computers, which IBM would heavily market and would eventually become one of the best-selling series of notebook computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1993, IBM posted an $8 billion loss – at the time the biggest in American corporate history.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Lou Gerstner was hired as CEO from RJR Nabisco to turn the company around.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1995, IBM purchased Lotus Development Corporation, best known for its Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet software.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] During the decade, IBM was working on a new operating system, named the Workplace OS project.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Despite a large amount of money spent on the project, it was cancelled in 1996.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1998, IBM merged the enterprise-oriented Personal Systems Group of the IBM PC Co. into IBM's own Global Services personal computer consulting and customer service division.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The resulting merged business units then became known simply as IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] A year later, IBM stopped selling its computers at retail outlets after its market share in this sector had fallen considerably behind competitors Compaq and Dell.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Immediately afterwards, the IBM PC Co. was dissolved and merged into IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In the 2000s, IBM collaborated with the Chinese defense contractor Huadi to develop the “Golden Shield Project”, a large-scale policing and surveillance project in Beijing.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The system was reportedly used to monitor online activity and target groups such as Falun Gong, Uyghurs and other individuals considered security risks.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2002, IBM acquired PwC Consulting, the consulting arm of PwC which was merged into its IBM Global Services.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On September 14, 2004, LG and IBM announced that their business alliance in the South Korean market would end at the end of that year.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Both companies stated that it was unrelated to the charges of bribery earlier that year.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Xnote was originally part of the joint venture and was sold by LG in 2012.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Continuing a trend started in the 1990s of downsizing its operations and divesting from commodity production, IBM sold all of its personal computer business to Chinese technology company Lenovo, and in 2009, it acquired software company SPSS Inc.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Later in 2009, IBM's Blue Gene supercomputing program was awarded the National Medal of Technology and Innovation by U.S.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2011, an IBM-owned artificial intelligence program called Watson was exhibited on *Jeopardy!* where it won against game-show champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company also celebrated its 100th anniversary in the same year on June 16.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2012, IBM announced it had agreed to buy Kenexa and Texas Memory Systems, and a year later it also acquired SoftLayer Technologies, a web hosting service, in a deal worth around $2 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Also that year, the company designed a video surveillance system for Davao City.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2014, IBM announced it would sell its x86 server division to Lenovo for $2.1 billion while continuing to offer Power ISA-based servers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Also that year, IBM began announcing several major partnerships with other companies, including Apple Inc., Twitter, Facebook, Tencent, Cisco, UnderArmour, Box, Microsoft, VMware, CSC, Macy's, Sesame Workshop, the parent company of Sesame Street, and Salesforce.com.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2015, its chip division transitioned to a fabless model with semiconductors design, offloading manufacturing to GlobalFoundries.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2015, IBM announced three major acquisitions: Merge Healthcare for $1 billion, data storage vendor Cleversafe, and all digital assets from The Weather Company, including Weather.com and The Weather Channel mobile app.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Also that year, IBM employees created the film *A Boy and His Atom*, which was the first molecule movie to tell a story.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2016, IBM acquired video conferencing service Ustream and formed a new cloud video unit.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In April 2016, it posted a 14-year low in quarterly sales.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The following month, Groupon sued IBM accusing it of patent infringement, two months after IBM accused Groupon of patent infringement in a separate lawsuit.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2016, IBM bought Truven Health Analytics for $2.6 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In October 2018, IBM announced its intention to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion, which was completed on July 9, 2019.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In February 2020, IBM's John Kelly III joined Brad Smith of Microsoft to sign a pledge with the Vatican to ensure the ethical use and practice of Artificial Intelligence (AI).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM announced in October 2020 that it would divest the Managed Infrastructure Services unit of its Global Technology Services division into a new public company.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The new company, Kyndryl, will have 90,000 employees, 4,600 clients in 115 countries, with an order backlog of $60 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's spin-off was greater than any of its previous divestitures, and welcomed by investors.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM appointed Martin Schroeter, who had been IBM's CFO from 2014 through the end of 2017, as CEO of Kyndryl.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2021, IBM announced the acquisition of the enterprise software company Turbonomic for $1.5 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In January 2022, IBM announced it would sell Watson Health to private equity firm Francisco Partners.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On March 7, 2022, a few days after the start of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, IBM CEO Arvind Krishna announced that "we have suspended all business in Russia".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] All Russian articles were also removed from the IBM website.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On June 7, Krishna announced that IBM would carry out an "orderly wind-down" of its operations in Russia.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In late 2022, IBM started a collaboration with new Japanese manufacturer Rapidus, which led GlobalFoundries to file a lawsuit against IBM the following year.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2023, IBM acquired Manta Software Inc. to complement its data and A.I. governance capabilities for an undisclosed amount.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On November 16, 2023, IBM suspended ads on Twitter after ads were found next to pro-Nazi content.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In August 2023, IBM agreed to sell The Weather Company to Francisco Partners for an undisclosed sum.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The sale was finalized on February 1, 2024, and the price was disclosed as $1.1 billion, with $750 million in cash, $100 million deferred over seven years, and $250 million in contingent consideration.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In December 2023, IBM announced it would acquire Software AG's StreamSets and webMethods platforms for €2.13 billion ($2.33 billion).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On December 8, 2025, IBM announced a deal to acquire data-infrastructure company Confluent for approximately $11 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The deal closed in March 2026 and was expected to help further advance the company's interests in AI.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] On June 25, 2026, IBM unveiled the world's first technology capable of producing chips smaller than 1 nanometer.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's market capitalization was valued at over $153 billion as of May 2024.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Despite its relative decline within the technology sector, IBM remains the seventh largest technology company by revenue, and 68th largest overall company by revenue in the United States.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] 38 on the 2020 Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2014, IBM was accused of using "financial engineering" to hit its quarterly earnings targets rather than investing for the longer term.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2018, IBM along with 91 additional *Fortune* 500 companies had "paid an effective federal tax rate of 0% or less" as a result of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM Q1 2024 revenue alone was $14.5 billion, up 1% year-over-year.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company's software revenue was up 5% with strong performance in hybrid cloud and AI.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The full FY2024 figure and FY2024 figure and FY2025 quarterly results need updating throughout the article.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company's 15-member board of directors are responsible for overall corporate management and includes the current or former CEOs of Anthem, Dow Chemical, Johnson and Johnson, Royal Dutch Shell, UPS, and Vanguard as well as the president of Cornell University and a retired U.S.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Vanguard Group is the largest shareholder of IBM and as of March 31, 2023, held 15.7% of total shares outstanding.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2011, IBM became the first technology company Warren Buffett's holding company Berkshire Hathaway invested in.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Initially he bought 64 million shares costing $10.5 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Over the years, Buffett increased his IBM holdings, but by the end of 2017 had reduced them by 94.5% to 2.05 million shares; by May 2018, he was completely out of IBM.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM is headquartered in Armonk, New York, a community 37 miles (60 km) north of Midtown Manhattan.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] A nickname for the company is the "**Colossus of Armonk**".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Its principal building, referred to as CHQ, is a 283,000-square-foot (26,300 m2) glass and stone edifice on a 25-acre (10 ha) parcel amid a 432-acre former apple orchard the company purchased in the mid-1950s.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] There are two other IBM buildings within walking distance of CHQ: the North Castle office, which previously served as IBM's headquarters; and the Louis V.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Gerstner, Jr., Center for Learning (formerly known as IBM Learning Center (ILC)), a resort hotel and training center, which has 182 guest rooms, 31 meeting rooms, and various amenities.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM operates in 174 countries as of 2016, with mobility centers in smaller market areas and major campuses in the larger ones.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In New York City, IBM has several offices besides CHQ, including the IBM Watson headquarters at Astor Place in Manhattan.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Outside of New York, major campuses in the United States include Austin, Texas; Research Triangle Park (Raleigh-Durham), North Carolina; Rochester, Minnesota; and Silicon Valley, California.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's real estate holdings are varied and globally diverse.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Towers occupied by IBM include 1250 René-Lévesque (Montreal, Canada) and One Atlantic Center (Atlanta, Georgia, US).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In Beijing, China, IBM occupies Pangu Plaza, the city's seventh tallest building and overlooking Beijing National Stadium ("Bird's Nest"), home to the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM India Private Limited is the Indian subsidiary of IBM, which is headquartered at Bangalore, Karnataka.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It has facilities in Coimbatore, Chennai, Kochi, Ahmedabad, Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Pune, Gurugram, Noida, Bhubaneshwar, Surat, Visakhapatnam, Hyderabad, Bangalore and Jamshedpur.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Defunct IBM campuses include the IBM Somers Office Complex (Somers, New York), Spango Valley (Greenock, Scotland), and Tour Descartes (Paris, France).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company's contributions to industrial architecture and design include works by Marcel Breuer, Eero Saarinen, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, I.M.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Van der Rohe's building in Chicago was recognized with the 1990 Honor Award from the National Building Museum.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2004, concerns were raised related to IBM's contribution in its early days to pollution in its original location in Endicott, New York.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM reported its total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 621 kilotons (-324 /-34.3% year-on-year).
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In February 2021, IBM committed to achieve net zero greenhouse gas emissions by the year 2030.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] However, there is no evidence that IBM has actually made any substantial changes to actually do so.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM has a large and diverse portfolio of products and services.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] As of 2016, these offerings fall into the categories of cloud computing, artificial intelligence, commerce, data and analytics, Internet of things (IoT), IT infrastructure, mobile, digital workplace and cybersecurity.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Since 1954, IBM has sold mainframe computers, the latest being the IBM z series.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The most recent model, the IBM z17, was released in 2025.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 1990, IBM released the Power microprocessors, which were designed into many console gaming systems, including Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, and Nintendo's Wii U.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2016, the company launched all-flash arrays designed for small and midsized companies, which includes software for data compression, provisioning, and snapshots across various systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In January 2019, IBM introduced its first commercial quantum computer: IBM Q System One.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In March 2020, it was announced that IBM would build Europe's first quantum data center in Ehningen, Germany.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The center, operated by the Fraunhofer Society, was opened in 2024.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Since 2009, IBM has owned SPSS, a software package used for statistical analysis in the social sciences.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM also owned The Weather Company, which provides weather forecasting and includes weather.com and Weather Underground, which was sold in 2024.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM Cloud includes infrastructure as a service (IaaS), software as a service (SaaS) and platform as a service (PaaS) offered through public, private and hybrid cloud delivery models.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] For instance, the IBM Bluemix PaaS enables developers to quickly create complex websites on a pay-as-you-go model.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM SoftLayer is a dedicated server, managed hosting and cloud computing provider, which in 2011 reported hosting more than 81,000 servers for more than 26,000 customers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM also provides Cloud Data Encryption Services (ICDES), using cryptographic splitting to secure customer data.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In May 2022, IBM announced the company had signed a multi-year Strategic Collaboration Agreement with Amazon Web Services to make a wide variety of IBM software available as a service on AWS Marketplace.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Additionally, the deal includes both companies making joint investments that make it easier for companies to consume IBM's offering and integrate them with AWS, including developer training and software development for select markets.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM Watson is a technology platform that uses natural language processing and machine learning to reveal insights from large amounts of unstructured data.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson was debuted in 2011 on the American game show *Jeopardy!*, where it competed against champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter in a three-game tournament and won.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson has since been applied to business, healthcare, developers, and universities.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] For example, IBM has partnered with Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center to assist with considering treatment options for oncology patients and for doing melanoma screenings.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Several companies use Watson for call centers, either replacing or assisting customer service agents.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM also provides infrastructure for the New York City Police Department through its IBM Cognos Analytics to perform data visualizations of CompStat crime data.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In June 2020, IBM announced that it was exiting the facial recognition business.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In May 2023, IBM revealed Watsonx, a Generative AI toolkit that is powered by IBM's own Granite models with option to use other publicly available LLMs.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watsonx has multiple services for training and fine tuning models based on confidential data.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] A year later, IBM open-sourced Granite code models and put them on Hugging Face for public use.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In October 2024, IBM introduced Granite 3.0, an open-source large language model designed for enterprise AI applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] With 160,000 consultants globally as of 2024, IBM is one of the ten largest consulting companies in the world, with capabilities spanning strategy and management consulting, experience design, technology and systems integration, and operations.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's consulting business was valued at $20 billion, as of 2024.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Now, IBM Research constitutes the largest industrial research organization in the world, with 12 labs on 6 continents.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM Research is headquartered at the Thomas J.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In terms of investment, IBM's R&D expenditure totals several billion dollars each year.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2012, that expenditure was approximately $6.9 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Recent allocations have included $1 billion to create a business unit for Watson in 2014, and $3 billion to create a next-gen semiconductor along with $4 billion towards growing the company's "strategic imperatives" (cloud, analytics, mobile, security, social) in 2015.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2024, IBM reported research and development expenditures of $7.48 billion, representing an increase of approximately 10.3% compared to the previous year’s expenditure of $6.78 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM has been a leading proponent of the Open Source Initiative, and began supporting Linux in 1998.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company invests billions of dollars in services and software based on Linux through the IBM Linux Technology Center, which includes over 300 Linux kernel developers.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's open source involvement has not been trouble-free, however (see *SCO v.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Additionally, in 1990 company scientists used a scanning tunneling microscope to arrange 35 individual xenon atoms to spell out the company initialism, marking the first structure assembled one atom at a time.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] A major part of IBM research is the generation of patents.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Since its first patent for a traffic signaling device, IBM has been one of the world's most prolific patent sources.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2021, the company held the record for most patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years for the achievement.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] As of 2021, IBM holds the record for most annual U.S. patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In 2001, IBM became the first company to generate more than 3,000 patents in one year, beating this record in 2008 with over 4,000 patents.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM has also been criticized as being a patent troll.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM is nicknamed *Big Blue* partly because of its blue logo and color scheme, and also in reference to its former *de facto* dress code of white shirts with blue suits.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company logo has undergone several changes over the years, with its current "8-bar" logo designed in 1972 by graphic designer Paul Rand.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] It was a general replacement for a 13-bar logo, since period photocopiers did not render narrow (as opposed to tall) stripes well.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Aside from the logo, IBM used Helvetica as a corporate typeface for 50 years, until it was replaced in 2017 by the custom-designed IBM Plex.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM has a valuable brand as a result of over 100 years of operations and marketing campaigns.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] As a result, IBM CEO Ginni Rometty became the third female member of the Master's governing body, the Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM is also a major sponsor in professional tennis, with engagements at the U.S.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Open, Wimbledon, the Australian Open, and the French Open.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company also sponsored the Olympic Games from 1960 to 2000, and the National Football League from 2003 to 2012.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In Japan, IBM employees also have an American football team complete with pro stadium, cheerleaders and televised games, competing in the Japanese X-League as the "Big Blue".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM is among the world's largest employers, with over 297,900 employees worldwide in 2022, with about 160,000 of those being tech consultants.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's leadership programs include Extreme Blue, an internship program, and the IBM Fellow award, offered since 1963 based on technical achievement.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Many IBM employees have achieved notability outside of work and after leaving IBM.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Other former IBM employees include NASA astronaut Michael J.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Massimino, Canadian astronaut and former Governor General Julie Payette, noted musician Dave Matthews, Harvey Mudd College president Maria Klawe, Western Governors University president emeritus Robert Mendenhall, former University of Kentucky president Lee T.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Todd Jr., former University of Iowa president Bruce Harreld, NFL referee Bill Carollo, former Rangers F.C. chairman John McClelland, and recipient of the Nobel Prize in Literature J.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Thomas Watson Jr. also served as the 11th national president of the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Five IBM employees have received the Nobel Prize: Leo Esaki, of the Thomas J.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., in 1973, for work in semiconductors; Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer, of the Zurich Research Center, in 1986, for the scanning tunneling microscope; and Georg Bednorz and Alex Müller, also of Zurich, in 1987, for research in superconductivity.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Six IBM employees have won the Turing Award, including the first female recipient Frances E.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Ten National Medals of Technology and five National Medals of Science have been awarded to IBM employees.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Employees are often referred to as "IBMers" and "Once An IBMer, Always An IBMer.".
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] IBM's culture has evolved significantly over its century of operations.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] In its early days, a dark (or gray) suit, white shirt, and a "sincere" tie constituted the public uniform for IBM employees.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] During IBM's management transformation in the 1990s, CEO Louis V.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Gerstner Jr. relaxed these codes, normalizing the dress and behavior of IBM employees.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] Similar IBM backronyms exist within the industry, such as Computerworld producing a badge labelled "It's Better Manually" implying it would be easier to use a paper-based system than a computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/ibm] The company has traditionally resisted labor union organizing, although unions represent some IBM workers outside the United States.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] A mainframe computer is large but not as large as a supercomputer and has more processing power than some other classes of computers, such as minicomputers, workstations, and personal computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Most large-scale computer-system architectures were established in the 1960s, but they continue to evolve.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframe computers are often used as servers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The term *mainframe* was derived from the large cabinet, called a *main frame*, that housed the central processing unit and main memory of early computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Later, the term *mainframe* was used to distinguish high-end commercial computers from less powerful machines.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The high stability and reliability of mainframes enable these machines to run uninterrupted for very long periods of time, with mean time between failures (MTBF) measured in decades.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframes have high availability, one of the primary reasons for their longevity, since they are typically used in applications where downtime would be costly or catastrophic.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] High levels of reliability, availability and serviceability (RAS) is a defining characteristic of mainframe computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In the late 1950s, mainframes had only a rudimentary interactive interface (the console) and used sets of punched cards, paper tape, or magnetic tape to transfer data and programs.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] They operated in batch mode to support back office functions such as payroll and customer billing, most of which were based on repeated tape-based sorting and merging operations followed by line printing to preprinted continuous stationery.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] When interactive user terminals were introduced, they were used almost exclusively for applications (e.g. airline booking) rather than program development.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] However, in 1961 the first academic, general-purpose timesharing system that supported software development, CTSS, was released at MIT on an IBM 709, later 7090 and 7094.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Typewriter and Teletype devices were common control consoles for system operators through the early 1970s, although ultimately supplanted by keyboard/display devices.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] By the early 1970s, many mainframes acquired interactive user terminals operating as timesharing computers, supporting hundreds of users simultaneously along with batch processing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Users gained access through keyboard/typewriter terminals and later character-mode text terminal cathode-ray tube displays with integral keyboards, or finally from personal computers equipped with terminal emulation software.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] By the 1980s, many mainframes supported general purpose graphic display terminals, and terminal emulation, but not graphical user interfaces.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] This form of end-user computing became obsolete in the 1990s due to the advent of personal computers provided with graphical user interfaces.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] After 2000, modern mainframes partially or entirely phased out classic "green screen" and color display terminal access for end-users in favour of Web-style user interfaces.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The infrastructure requirements were drastically reduced during the mid-1990s, when CMOS mainframe designs replaced the older bipolar technology.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM claimed that its newer mainframes reduced data center energy costs for power and cooling, and reduced physical space requirements compared to server farms.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Modern mainframes can run multiple different instances of operating systems at the same time.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] This technique of virtual machines allows applications to run as if they were on physically distinct computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In this role, a single mainframe can replace higher-functioning hardware services available to conventional servers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] While mainframes pioneered this capability, virtualization is now available on most families of computer systems, though not always to the same degree or level of sophistication.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframes can add or hot swap system capacity without disrupting system function, with specificity and granularity to a level of sophistication not usually available with most server solutions.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Modern mainframes, notably the IBM Z servers, offer two levels of virtualization: logical partitions (LPARs, via the PR/SM facility) and virtual machines (via the z/VM operating system).
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Many mainframe customers run two machines: one in their primary data center and one in their backup data center—fully active, partially active, or on standby—in case there is a catastrophe affecting the first building.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Test, development, training, and production workload for applications and databases can run on a single machine, except for extremely large demands where the capacity of one machine might be limiting.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Such a two-mainframe installation can support continuous business service, avoiding both planned and unplanned outages.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In practice, many customers use multiple mainframes linked either by Parallel Sysplex and shared DASD (in IBM's case), or with shared, geographically dispersed storage provided by EMC or Hitachi.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframes are designed to handle very high volume input and output (I/O) and emphasize throughput computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Since the late 1950s, mainframe designs have included subsidiary hardware (called *channels* or *peripheral processors*) which manage the I/O devices, leaving the CPU free to deal only with high-speed memory.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] It is common in mainframe shops to deal with massive databases and files.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Gigabyte to terabyte-size record files are not unusual.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Compared to a typical PC, mainframes commonly have hundreds to thousands of times as much data storage online, and can access it reasonably quickly.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Other server families also offload I/O processing and emphasize throughput computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframe return on investment (ROI), like any other computing platform, is dependent on its ability to scale, support mixed workloads, reduce labor costs, deliver uninterrupted service for critical business applications, and several other risk-adjusted cost factors.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframes also have execution integrity characteristics for fault tolerant computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] This hardware-level feature, also found in HP's NonStop systems, is known as lock-stepping, because both processors take their "steps" (i.e. instructions) together.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Not all applications absolutely need the assured integrity that these systems provide, but many do, such as financial transaction processing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] A **mainframe audit** is a comprehensive inspection of computer processes, security, and procedures, with recommendations for improvement.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Organizations in different industries have different auditing and security requirements.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Some factors affecting the organizations' requirements are: regulatory requirements and other external factors; management, objectives, and business practices; and the organizations' performance compared to the industry.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] This information can be obtained by conducting outside research, interviewing employees, touring the data center and observing activities, consultations with technical experts, and looking at company manuals and business plans.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Another consideration is the level of mainframe access employees have and if password policies are in place and followed.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Evidence of implementation can be obtained by requesting employee manuals, evaluating the software and user histories, and by physical observation of the environment.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Physical access is also an area of interest.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Are cables adequately protected from damage and sniffing between the Network and the Data Center?
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] This can be achieved by proper routing of the cables, encryption, and a good network topology.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Physical observation of where the cables are routed and confirmation of the security procedures should be obtained.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Tests of controls should be conducted to determine any additional weaknesses.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Does the mainframe have access to an adequate uninterruptible power supply?
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Are physical controls such as power badges for access, fire suppression devices, and locks in place to protect the data center (and the mainframe inside) from theft, manipulation or damage?
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Physical observation is necessary to ensure these requirements.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM, with the IBM Z series, continues to be a major manufacturer in the mainframe market.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In 2000, Hitachi co-developed the zSeries z900 with IBM to share expenses, and the latest Hitachi AP10000 models are made by IBM.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Unisys manufactures ClearPath Libra mainframes, based on earlier Burroughs MCP products and ClearPath Dorado mainframes based on Sperry Univac OS 1100 product lines.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Hewlett Packard Enterprise sells its unique NonStop systems, which it acquired with Tandem Computers and which some analysts classify as mainframes.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Groupe Bull's GCOS, Stratus OpenVOS, Fujitsu (formerly Siemens) BS2000, and Fujitsu-ICL VME mainframes are still available in Europe, and Fujitsu (formerly Amdahl) GS21 mainframes globally.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] NEC with ACOS and Hitachi with AP10000-VOS3 still maintain mainframe businesses in the Japanese market.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The amount of vendor investment in mainframe development varies with market share.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Fujitsu and Hitachi both continue to use custom S/390-compatible processors, as well as other CPUs (including POWER and Xeon) for lower-end systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Bull uses a mixture of Itanium and Xeon processors.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] NEC uses Xeon processors for its low-end ACOS-2 line, but develops the custom NOAH-6 processor for its high-end ACOS-4 series.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM also develops custom processors in-house, such as the Telum.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Unisys produces code compatible mainframe systems that range from laptops to cabinet-sized mainframes that use homegrown CPUs as well as Xeon processors.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Furthermore, there exists a market for software applications to manage the performance of mainframe implementations.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In addition to IBM, significant market competitors include BMC and Precisely; former competitors include Compuware and CA Technologies.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Several manufacturers and their successors produced mainframe computers from the 1950s until the early 21st century, with gradually decreasing numbers and a gradual transition to simulation on Intel chips rather than proprietary hardware.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The US group of manufacturers was first known as "IBM and the Seven Dwarfs": usually Burroughs, UNIVAC, NCR, Control Data, Honeywell, General Electric and RCA, although some lists varied.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Later, with the departure of General Electric and RCA, it was referred to as IBM and the BUNCH.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM's dominance grew out of their 700/7000 series and, later, the development of the 360 series mainframes.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The latter architecture has continued to evolve into their current zSeries mainframes which, along with the then Burroughs and Sperry (now Unisys) MCP-based and OS1100 mainframes, are among the few mainframe architectures still extant that can trace their roots to this early period.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] While IBM's zSeries can still run 24-bit System/360 code, the 64-bit IBM Z CMOS servers have nothing physically in common with the older systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Notable manufacturers outside the US were Siemens and Telefunken in Germany, ICL in the United Kingdom, Olivetti in Italy, and Fujitsu, Hitachi, Oki, and NEC in Japan.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The Soviet Union and Warsaw Pact countries manufactured close copies of IBM mainframes during the Cold War; the BESM series and Strela are examples of independently designed Soviet computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Elwro in Poland was another Eastern Bloc manufacturer, producing the ODRA, R-32 and R-34 mainframes.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In 1984, estimated sales of desktop computers ($11.6 billion) exceeded mainframe computers ($11.4 billion) for the first time.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM received the vast majority of mainframe revenue.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] During the 1980s, minicomputer-based systems grew more sophisticated and were able to displace the lower end of the mainframes.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] These computers, sometimes called *departmental computers*, were typified by the Digital Equipment Corporation VAX series.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In 1991, AT&T Corporation briefly owned NCR.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] During the same period, companies found that servers based on microcomputer designs could be deployed at a fraction of the acquisition price and offer local users much greater control over their own systems given the IT policies and practices at that time.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Terminals used for interacting with mainframe systems were gradually replaced by personal computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Consequently, demand plummeted and new mainframe installations were restricted mainly to financial services and government.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In the early 1990s, there was a rough consensus among industry analysts that the mainframe was a dying market as mainframe platforms were increasingly replaced by personal computer networks.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] *InfoWorld*'s Stewart Alsop infamously predicted that the last mainframe would be unplugged in 1996; in 1993, he cited Cheryl Currid, a computer industry analyst as saying that the last mainframe "will stop working on December 31, 1999", a reference to the anticipated Year 2000 problem (Y2K).
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] That trend started to turn around in the late 1990s as corporations found new uses for their existing mainframes and as the price of data networking collapsed in most parts of the world, encouraging trends toward more centralized computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The growth of e-business also dramatically increased the number of back-end transactions processed by mainframe software as well as the size and throughput of databases.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Batch processing, such as billing, became even more important (and larger) with the growth of e-business, and mainframes are particularly adept at large-scale batch computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Another factor currently increasing mainframe use is the development of the Linux operating system, which arrived on IBM mainframe systems in 1999.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Linux allows users to take advantage of open source software combined with mainframe hardware RAS.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM's quarterly and annual reports in the 2000s usually reported increasing mainframe revenues and capacity shipments.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] However, IBM's mainframe hardware business has not been immune to the recent overall downturn in the server hardware market or to model cycle effects.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] For example, in the 4th quarter of 2009, IBM's System z hardware revenues decreased by 27% year over year.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] But MIPS (millions of instructions per second) shipments increased 4% per year over the past two years.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Alsop had himself photographed in 2000, symbolically eating his own words ("death to the mainframe").
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In 2012, NASA powered down its last mainframe, an IBM System z9.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] As of 2010, while mainframe technology represented less than 3% of IBM's revenues, it "continue[d] to play an outsized role in Big Blue's results".
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] IBM has continued to launch new generations of mainframes: the IBM z13 in 2015, the z14 in 2017, the z15 in 2019, and the z16 in 2022, the latter featuring among other things an "integrated on-chip AI accelerator" and the new Telum microprocessor.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] A supercomputer is a computer at the leading edge of data processing capability, with respect to calculation speed.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Supercomputers are used for scientific and engineering problems (high-performance computing) which crunch numbers and data, while mainframes focus on transaction processing.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] Mainframes and supercomputers cannot always be clearly distinguished; up until the early 1990s, many supercomputers were based on a mainframe architecture with supercomputing extensions.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] An example of such a system is the HITAC S-3800, which was instruction-set compatible with IBM System/370 mainframes, and could run the Hitachi VOS3 operating system (a fork of IBM MVS).
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] The S-3800 therefore can be seen as being both simultaneously a supercomputer and also an IBM-compatible mainframe.
[src:ibm-cloud/mainframe-computer] In 2007, an amalgamation of the different technologies and architectures for supercomputers and mainframes has led to a so-called gameframe.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] The family's other products provide this platform through different environments.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Deployment methods include self-managed; cloud native under **ROSA** (Red Hat OpenShift Service on AWS), **ARO** (Azure Red Hat OpenShift) and **RHOIC** (Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud); OpenShift Online as software as a service; and OpenShift Dedicated as a managed service.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] The OpenShift Console has developer and administrator oriented views.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Administrator views allow one to monitor container resources and health, manage users and work with operators.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Developer views are oriented around working with application resources within a namespace.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift also provides a CLI that supports a superset of the actions provided by the Kubernetes CLI.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift originated from Red Hat's acquisition of Makara, a company marketing a platform as a service (PaaS) based on Linux containers, in November 2010.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] It was announced in May 2011 as proprietary technology and only became open-source in May 2012.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Until version 3, released in June 2015, OpenShift used custom developed technologies.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Version 3 adopted Docker as the container technology and Kubernetes as the orchestration engine.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Version 4 further changed the architecture, notably adopting CRI-O as the container runtime (and Podman for interacting with pods and containers), and Buildah as the container build tool, thus removing the dependency on Docker.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Online offered version 2 of the OKD project source code, which is also available under the Apache License Version 2.0.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] This version supported a variety of languages, frameworks, and databases via pre-built "cartridges" running under resource-quota "gears".
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Developers could add other languages, databases, or components via the OpenShift Cartridge application programming interface.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] This was deprecated in favour of OpenShift 3, and was withdrawn on 30 September 2017 for non-paying customers and 31 December 2017 for paying customers.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] The main difference between OpenShift and vanilla Kubernetes is its extension of the platform with build-related artifacts as first-class Kubernetes resources upon which standard Kubernetes operations can apply.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift's *oc* client offers a superset of the standard *kubectl* (Kubernetes standard client) capabilities., including direct interaction with build resources via sub-commands like *new-build* or *start-build*.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] It also provided out of the box an OpenShift-native pod builds technology called Source-to-Image (S2I), though this is slowly being phased out in favor of Tekton, a cloud-native CI/CD framework for Kubernetes.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Unique resources like ImageStreams (a sequence of pointers to images which can be associated with deployments) and Templates (a packaging mechanism for application components).
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] The *new-app* command, which initiates an application deployment, automatically applies the *app* label (with the value of the label taken from the *--name* argument) to all created resources, simplifying management.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Support for multiple infrastructure platforms, including AWS, Azure, IBM Cloud, vSphere, and bare metal.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift’s implementation of Deployment, called DeploymentConfig is logic-based in comparison to Kubernetes' controller-based Deployment objects.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] As of v4.5, OpenShift is steering more towards Deployments by changing the default behavior of its CLI.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] An embedded OperatorHub, a web GUI for browsing and installing a library of Kubernetes Operators packaged for easy life cycle management, including Red Hat authored Operators, Red Hat Certified Operators and Community Operators.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift v4 tightly controls the operating systems for "control plane" components.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] They must run on Red Hat CoreOS, enabling automated, reliable upgrades and patches.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] The compute (worker) nodes can run any Linux OS or even Windows.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift introduced the concept of *routes* -- points of traffic ingress into the cluster.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] This later influenced the Kubernetes ingress concept.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift also bundles various software components from the Kubernetes ecosystem for enhanced functionality.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] For observability, it includes Prometheus, Fluentd, Vector, Loki, and Istio (branded as Red Hat Service Mesh, based on the Maistra open source project).
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OKD, known until August 2018 as OpenShift Origin (Origin Community Distribution) is the upstream community project for OpenShift.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Built around a core of CRI-O container runtime and Kubernetes cluster management, OKD is augmented by application life cycle management functionality and DevOps tooling.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] All source code for the OKD project is available under the Apache License (Version 2.0) on GitHub.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Red Hat OpenShift Online (RHOO) is a public cloud application development and hosting software as a service (SaaS) that runs on AWS and IBM Cloud.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift Online is limited to running containers that do not require root.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift Dedicated (OSD) is Red Hat's managed private cluster offering on the marketplaces of Amazon Web Services (AWS), IBM Cloud, Google Cloud Platform (GCP) since December 2016.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] A similar managed service is offered on Microsoft Azure under the name Azure Red Hat OpenShift (ARO).
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] OpenShift Data Foundation (ODF) provides cloud-native storage, data management and data protection for applications running on the OpenShift platform in cloud, on-premises, and hybrid/multi-cloud environments.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Red Hat OpenShift Database Access (RHODA) is a capability for managed OpenShift environments (OSD and ROSA) that enables administrators to set up connections to database-as-a-service offerings from different providers.
[src:ibm-cloud/openshift] Its initial alpha release included support for MongoDB Atlas for MongoDB and Crunchy Bridge for PostgreSQL.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A **quantum computer** is a real or theoretical computer that exploits quantum phenomena like superposition and entanglement in an essential way.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] It is widely believed that a quantum computer could perform *some* calculations exponentially faster than any classical computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] For example, a large-scale quantum computer could break some widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, current hardware implementations of quantum computation are largely experimental and only suitable for specialized tasks.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The basic unit of information in quantum computing, the qubit (or "quantum bit"), serves the same function as the bit in ordinary or "classical" computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, unlike a classical bit, which can be in one of two states (a binary), a qubit can exist in a linear combination of two states known as a quantum superposition.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The result of measuring a qubit is one of the two states given by a probabilistic rule.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] If a quantum computer manipulates the qubit in a particular way, wave interference effects amplify the probability of the desired measurement result.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The design of quantum algorithms involves creating procedures that allow a quantum computer to perform this amplification.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are not yet practical for real-world applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Physically engineering high-quality qubits has proven to be challenging.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] If a physical qubit is not sufficiently isolated from its environment, it suffers from quantum decoherence, introducing noise into calculations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] National governments have invested heavily in experimental research aimed at developing scalable qubits with longer coherence times and lower error rates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Example implementations include superconductors (which isolate an electrical current by eliminating electrical resistance) and ion traps (which confine a single atomic particle using electromagnetic fields).
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Researchers have claimed, and are widely believed to be correct, that certain quantum devices can outperform classical computers on narrowly defined tasks, a milestone referred to as quantum advantage or quantum supremacy.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These tasks are not necessarily useful for real-world applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] As a result, current demonstrations are best understood as scientific milestones rather than evidence of broad near-term deployment.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In December 2024, Google's Willow chip achieved below-threshold error correction, a milestone 30 years in the making, while global government investment in quantum computing reached $10 billion by April 2025.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] For many years, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science formed distinct academic communities.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Modern quantum theory was developed in the 1920s to explain perplexing physical phenomena observed at atomic scales, and digital computers emerged in the following decades to replace human computers for tedious calculations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Both disciplines had practical applications during World War II; computers played a major role in wartime cryptography, and quantum physics was essential for nuclear physics used in the Manhattan Project.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] As physicists applied quantum mechanical models to computational problems and swapped digital bits for qubits, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science began to converge.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In 1980, Paul Benioff introduced the quantum Turing machine, which uses quantum theory to describe a simplified computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] When digital computers became faster, physicists faced an exponential increase in overhead when simulating quantum dynamics, prompting Yuri Manin and Richard Feynman to independently suggest that hardware based on quantum phenomena might be more efficient for computer simulation.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In a 1984 paper, Charles Bennett and Gilles Brassard applied quantum theory to cryptography protocols and demonstrated that quantum key distribution could enhance information security.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms then emerged for solving oracle problems, such as Deutsch's algorithm in 1985, the Bernstein–Vazirani algorithm in 1993, and Simon's algorithm in 1994.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms did not solve practical problems, but demonstrated mathematically that one could obtain more information by querying a black box with a quantum state in superposition, sometimes referred to as *quantum parallelism*.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Peter Shor built on these results with his 1994 algorithm for breaking the widely used RSA and Diffie–Hellman encryption protocols, which drew significant attention to the field of quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In 1996, Grover's algorithm established a quantum speedup for the widely applicable unstructured search problem.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The same year, Seth Lloyd proved that quantum computers could simulate quantum systems without the exponential overhead present in classical simulations, validating Feynman's 1982 conjecture.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Over the years, experimentalists have constructed small-scale quantum computers using trapped ions and superconductors.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In 1998, a two-qubit quantum computer demonstrated the feasibility of the technology, and subsequent experiments have increased the number of qubits and reduced error rates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Recent milestones in quantum computing have increasingly focused on controlling decoherence through quantum error correction.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In 2024, researchers demonstrated theoretical and practical approaches for high threshold, low-overhead fault-tolerant quantum memory.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These developments represent a critical step toward scaling systems beyond the noisy intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) era into reliable, fault-tolerant computing architectures, though large-scale physical implementation remains an ongoing engineering challenge.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Computer engineers typically describe a modern computer's operation in terms of classical electrodynamics.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In these "classical" computers, some components (such as semiconductors and random number generators) may rely on quantum behavior; however, because they are not isolated from their environment, any quantum information eventually quickly decoheres.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] While programmers may depend on probability theory when designing a randomized algorithm, quantum-mechanical notions such as superposition and wave interference are largely irrelevant in program analysis.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The "classical" in *classical computation* thus refers to the computational model, not to whether the microscopic physics of the hardware is ultimately quantum-mechanical.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A conventional digital computer can be described by classical states and transition rules: memory stores bits, while logic elements transform one configuration of bits into another.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This computational behavior is not tied to electronics, and can be abstracted through the idea of a Turing machine, a mechanical device that performs deterministic transformations on a finite state.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, the same classical transition rules can be implemented by some entirely classical mechanical device, possibly with a fixed slow-down in physical time.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] If a classical computation uses randomness, this can be modeled as access to random classical bits rather than as coherent quantum information.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computer, by contrast, uses coherent quantum states, so that superposition, relative phase, and interference are part of the computation itself, and has no classical counterpart.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum programs instead rely on precise control of coherent quantum systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists describe these systems mathematically using linear algebra.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Complex numbers model probability amplitudes, vectors model quantum states, and matrices model the operations that can be performed on these states.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Programming a quantum computer is then a matter of composing operations in such a way that the resulting program computes a useful result in theory and is implementable in practice.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Just as the bit is the basic concept of classical information theory, the *qubit* is the fundamental unit of quantum information.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The same term *qubit* is used to refer to an abstract mathematical model and to any physical system that is represented by that model.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A classical bit, by definition, exists in either of two physical states, which can be denoted 0 and 1.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A qubit is also described by a state, and two states, often written $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , serve as the quantum counterparts of the classical states 0 and 1.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, the quantum states $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ belong to a vector space, meaning that they can be multiplied by constants and added together, and the result is again a valid quantum state.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Such a combination is known as a *superposition* of $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ .
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A two-dimensional vector mathematically represents a qubit state.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists typically use bra–ket notation for quantum mechanical linear algebra, writing $|\psi \rangle$ 'ket psi' for a vector labeled $\psi$ .
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Because a qubit is a two-state system, any qubit state takes the form $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , where $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ are the standard *basis states*, and $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the *probability amplitudes,* which are in general complex numbers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] If either $\alpha$ or $\beta$ is zero, the qubit is effectively a classical bit; when both are nonzero, the qubit is in superposition.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Such a quantum state vector behaves similarly to a (classical) probability vector, with one key difference: unlike probabilities, probability *amplitudes* are not necessarily positive numbers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Negative amplitudes allow for destructive wave interference.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] When a qubit is measured in the standard basis, the result is a classical bit.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The Born rule describes the norm-squared correspondence between amplitudes and probabilities—when measuring a qubit $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , the state collapses to $|0\rangle$ with probability $|\alpha |^{2}$ , or to $|1\rangle$ with probability $|\beta |^{2}$ .
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Any valid qubit state has coefficients $\alpha$ and $\beta$ such that $|\alpha |^{2}+|\beta |^{2}=1$ .
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] As an example, measuring the qubit $1/{\sqrt {2}}|0\rangle +1/{\sqrt {2}}|1\rangle$ would produce either $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ with equal probability.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Each additional qubit doubles the dimension of the state space.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This vector inhabits a four-dimensional vector space spanned by the basis vectors |00⟩, |01⟩, |10⟩, and |11⟩.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In general, the vector space for an n-qubit system is 2*n*-dimensional, and this makes it challenging for a classical computer to simulate a quantum one: representing a 100-qubit system requires storing 2100 classical values.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The state of this one-qubit quantum memory can be manipulated by applying quantum logic gates, analogous to how classical memory can be manipulated with classical logic gates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] One important gate for both classical and quantum computation is the NOT gate, which can be represented by a matrix $X:={\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}}.$ Mathematically, the application of such a logic gate to a quantum state vector is modeled with matrix multiplication.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The mathematics of single-qubit gates can be extended to operate on multi-qubit quantum memories in two important ways.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] One way is simply to select a qubit and apply that gate to the target qubit while leaving the remainder of the memory unaffected.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Another way is to apply the gate to its target only if another part of the memory is in a desired state.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These two choices can be illustrated using another example.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In other words, the CNOT applies a NOT gate ( ${\textstyle X}$ from before) to the second qubit if and only if the first qubit is in the state ${\textstyle |1\rangle }$ .
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] If the first qubit is ${\textstyle |0\rangle }$ , nothing is done to either qubit.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In summary, quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, any measurement can be deferred to the end of quantum computation, though this deferment may come at a computational cost, so most quantum circuits depict a network consisting only of quantum logic gates and no measurements.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] There are multiple models of computation for quantum computing, distinguished by the basic elements in which the computation is decomposed.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum gate array decomposes computation into a sequence of few-qubit quantum gates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Any quantum computation (which is, in the above formalism, any unitary matrix of size $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ over n qubits) can be represented as a network of quantum logic gates from a fairly small family of gates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A choice of gate family that enables this construction is known as a universal gate set, since a computer that can run such circuits is a universal quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] One common such set includes all single-qubit gates as well as the CNOT gate from above.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This means any quantum computation can be performed by executing a sequence of single-qubit gates together with CNOT gates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Though this gate set is infinite, it can be replaced with a finite gate set by appealing to the Solovay-Kitaev theorem.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Implementation of Boolean functions using the few-qubit quantum gates is presented here.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A measurement-based quantum computer decomposes computation into a sequence of Bell state measurements and single-qubit quantum gates applied to a highly entangled initial state (a cluster state), using a technique called quantum gate teleportation.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] An adiabatic quantum computer, based on quantum annealing, decomposes computation into a slow continuous transformation of an initial Hamiltonian into a final Hamiltonian, whose ground states contain the solution.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing (abbreviated 'n.quantum computing') is an unconventional process of computing that uses neuromorphic computing to perform quantum operations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] It was suggested that quantum algorithms, which are algorithms that run on a realistic model of quantum computation, can be computed equally efficiently with neuromorphic quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Both traditional quantum computing and neuromorphic quantum computing are physics-based unconventional computing approaches to computations and do not follow the von Neumann architecture.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] They both construct a system (a circuit) that represents the physical problem at hand and then leverage their respective physics properties of the system to seek the "minimum".
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing and quantum computing share similar physical properties during computation.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A topological quantum computer decomposes computation into the braiding of anyons in a 2D lattice.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum Turing machine is the quantum analog of a Turing machine.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This equivalence need not hold for practical quantum computers, since the overhead of simulation may be too large to be practical.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The threshold theorem shows how increasing the number of qubits can mitigate errors, yet fully fault-tolerant quantum computing remains "a rather distant dream".
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] According to some researchers, *noisy intermediate-scale quantum* (NISQ) machines may have specialized uses in the near future, but noise in quantum gates limits their reliability.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Scientists at Harvard University successfully created "quantum circuits" that correct errors more efficiently than alternative methods, which may potentially remove a major obstacle to practical quantum computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The Harvard research team was supported by MIT, QuEra Computing, Caltech, and Princeton University and funded by DARPA's Optimization with Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum devices (ONISQ) program.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Digital cryptography enables communications to remain private, preventing unauthorized parties from accessing them.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Conventional encryption, the obscuring of a message with a key through an algorithm, relies on the algorithm being difficult to reverse.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Encryption is also the basis for digital signatures and authentication mechanisms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computing may be sufficiently more powerful that difficult reversals are feasible, allowing messages relying on conventional encryption to be read.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography replaces conventional algorithms with computations based on quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, quantum encryption would be impossible to decode even with a quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This advantage comes at a significant cost in terms of elaborate infrastructure, while effectively preventing legitimate decoding of messages by governmental security officials.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing research in quantum and post-quantum cryptography has led to new algorithms for quantum key distribution, initial work on quantum random number generation and to some early technology demonstrations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography enables new ways to transmit data securely; for example, quantum key distribution uses entangled quantum states to establish secure cryptographic keys.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] When a sender and receiver exchange quantum states, they can guarantee that an adversary does not intercept the message, as any unauthorized eavesdropper would disturb the delicate quantum system and introduce a detectable change.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] With appropriate cryptographic protocols, the sender and receiver can thus establish shared private information resistant to eavesdropping.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Modern fiber-optic cables can transmit quantum information over relatively short distances.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing experimental research aims to develop more reliable hardware (such as quantum repeaters), hoping to scale this technology to long-distance quantum networks with end-to-end entanglement.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Theoretically, this could enable novel technological applications, such as distributed quantum computing and enhanced quantum sensing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum teleportation is a protocol by which Alice can transmit the quantum state of a qubit to Bob using one shared entangled pair (e-bit) and two classical bits of communication.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The state of Alice's qubit is not physically transmitted—instead, it is reconstructed at Bob's end through classically communicated measurement outcomes and local unitary corrections.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This demonstrates that quantum communication requires both entanglement and classical communication; neither alone is sufficient.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Teleportation cannot be used to transmit information faster than light because the classical bits must travel through normal channels.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding is the complementary protocol: using one shared e-bit and sending only one qubit, Alice can transmit two classical bits to Bob.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This appears to violate Holevo's theorem—which states that a single qubit can carry at most one bit of classical information—but the shared entanglement circumvents this limit.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding thus demonstrates that entanglement can effectively double the classical information-carrying capacity of quantum communication.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Progress in finding quantum algorithms typically focuses on the quantum circuit model, though exceptions like the quantum adiabatic algorithm exist.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms can be roughly categorized by the type of speedup achieved over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms depend on the primitive of the quantum Fourier transform.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] No mathematical proof has been found that shows that an equally fast classical algorithm cannot be discovered, but evidence suggests that this is unlikely.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Certain oracle problems like Simon's problem and the Bernstein–Vazirani problem do give provable speedups, though this is in the quantum query model, which is a restricted model where lower bounds are much easier to prove and don't necessarily translate to speedups for practical problems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Because these problems are BQP-complete, an equally fast classical algorithm for them would imply that "no quantum algorithm" provides a super-polynomial speedup, which is believed to be unlikely.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Some quantum algorithms, such as Grover's algorithm and amplitude amplification, give polynomial speedups over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Though these algorithms give comparably modest quadratic speedup, they are widely applicable and thus give speedups for a wide range of problems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These speed-ups are, however, over the theoretical worst-case of classical algorithms, and concrete real-world speed-ups over algorithms used in practice have not been demonstrated.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Since chemistry and nanotechnology rely on understanding quantum systems, and such systems are impossible to simulate in an efficient manner classically, quantum simulation may be an important application of quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Recent reviews identify quantum chemistry as one of the most promising application areas for quantum computing, particularly for problems in electronic structure, chemical dynamics, and spectroscopy, while noting that useful implementations remain limited by current hardware.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulation could also be used to simulate the behavior of atoms and particles at unusual conditions such as the reactions inside a collider.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In June 2023, IBM computer scientists reported that a quantum computer produced better results for a physics problem than a conventional supercomputer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] About 2% of the annual global energy output is used for nitrogen fixation to produce ammonia for the Haber process in the agricultural fertiliser industry (even though naturally occurring organisms also produce ammonia).
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulations might be used to understand this process and increase the energy efficiency of production.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] It is expected that an early use of quantum computing will be modeling that improves the efficiency of the Haber–Bosch process by the mid-2020s although some have predicted it will take longer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A notable application of quantum computing is in attacking cryptographic systems that are currently in use.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Integer factorization, which underpins the security of public key cryptographic systems, is believed to be computationally infeasible on a classical computer for large integers if they are the product of a few prime numbers (e.g., the product of two 300-digit primes).
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] By contrast, a quantum computer could solve this problem exponentially faster using Shor's algorithm to factor the integer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This ability would allow a quantum computer to break many of the cryptographic systems in use today, in the sense that there would be a polynomial time (in the number of digits of the integer) algorithm for solving the problem.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, most of the popular public key ciphers are based on the difficulty of factoring integers or the discrete logarithm problem, both of which can be solved by Shor's algorithm.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, the RSA, Diffie–Hellman, and elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman algorithms could be broken.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] These are used to protect secure Web pages, encrypted email, and many other types of data.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking these would have significant ramifications for electronic privacy and security.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Identifying cryptographic systems that may be secure against quantum algorithms is an actively researched topic under the field of *post-quantum cryptography*.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Some public-key algorithms are based on problems other than the integer factorization and discrete logarithm problems to which Shor's algorithm applies, such as the McEliece cryptosystem, which relies on a hard problem in coding theory.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Lattice-based cryptosystems are also not known to be broken by quantum computers, and finding a polynomial time algorithm for solving the dihedral hidden subgroup problem, which would break many lattice-based cryptosystems, is a well-studied open problem.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The most well-known example of a problem that allows for a polynomial quantum speedup is *unstructured search*, which involves finding a marked item out of a list of n items in a database.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] This can be solved by Grover's algorithm using $O({\sqrt {n}})$ queries to the database, quadratically fewer than the $\Omega (n)$ queries required for classical algorithms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In this case, the advantage is not only provable but also optimal: it has been shown that Grover's algorithm gives the maximal possible probability of finding the desired element for any number of oracle lookups.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Many examples of provable quantum speedups for query problems are based on Grover's algorithm, including Brassard, Høyer, and Tapp's algorithm for finding collisions in two-to-one functions, and Farhi, Goldstone, and Gutmann's algorithm for evaluating NAND trees.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] There exists a Boolean function that evaluates each input and determines whether it is the correct answer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] For problems with all these properties, the running time of Grover's algorithm on a quantum computer scales as the square root of the number of inputs (or elements in the database), as opposed to the linear scaling of classical algorithms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A general class of problems to which Grover's algorithm can be applied is a Boolean satisfiability problem, where the *database* through which the algorithm iterates is that of all possible answers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] An example and possible application of this is a password cracker that attempts to guess a password.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking symmetric ciphers with this algorithm is of interest to government agencies.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing uses the adiabatic theorem to perform calculations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] A system is placed in the ground state for a simple Hamiltonian, which slowly evolves to a more complicated Hamiltonian whose ground state represents the solution to the problem in question.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] The adiabatic theorem states that if the evolution is slow enough, the system will stay in its ground state at all times through the process.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing can solve Ising models and the (computationally equivalent) QUBO problem, which in turn can be used to encode a wide range of combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Adiabatic optimization may be helpful for solving computational biology problems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Since quantum computers can produce outputs that classical computers cannot produce efficiently, and since quantum computation is fundamentally linear algebraic, some express hope in developing quantum algorithms that can speed up machine learning tasks.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, review literature notes that many proposed quantum machine-learning advantages rely on assumptions about efficient data encoding or continued access to quantum hardware, and have not yet translated into broad practical end-to-end advantage on current devices.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] For example, the HHL Algorithm, named after its discoverers Harrow, Hassidim, and Lloyd, is believed to provide speedup over classical counterparts.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Some research groups have recently explored the use of quantum annealing hardware for training Boltzmann machines and deep neural networks.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Deep generative chemistry models have been explored for potential applications in drug discovery.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Early experimental work has explored the use of near-term quantum hardware in molecular generative modeling for drug discovery.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] However, the immense size and complexity of the structural space of all possible drug-like molecules pose significant obstacles, which could be overcome in the future by quantum computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are naturally good for solving complex quantum many-body problems and thus may be instrumental in applications involving quantum chemistry.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Therefore, one can expect that quantum-enhanced generative models including quantum GANs may eventually be developed into ultimate generative chemistry algorithms.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] Artificial intelligence has also been explored as a tool for discovering and optimizing algorithms relevant to quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] AlphaEvolve, a Google DeepMind system based on large language models and evolutionary algorithms, has been described as a coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p01] In quantum-computing research, AlphaEvolve-optimized quantum circuits have been used in work on quantum computation of molecular geometry through many-body nuclear spin echoes.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2023, classical computers outperform quantum computers for all real-world applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] While current quantum computers may speed up solutions to particular mathematical problems, they give no computational advantage for practical tasks.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Scientists and engineers are exploring multiple technologies for quantum computing hardware and hope to develop scalable quantum architectures, but serious obstacles remain.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In practice, improvements in qubit counts alone are not enough, because error rates, connectivity, and data movement also affect whether an end-to-end application can outperform classical methods.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] There are a number of technical challenges in building a large-scale quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The control of multi-qubit systems requires the generation and coordination of a large number of electrical signals with tight and deterministic timing resolution.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] This has led to the development of quantum controllers that enable interfacing with the qubits.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Scaling these systems to support a growing number of qubits is an additional challenge.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The theoretical potential for large-scale quantum computers to eventually break widely used public-key encryption schemes has prompted significant motivated changes in global cybersecurity strategies.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In response to this future challenge, organizations, including the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), have initiated detailed standardization processes for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] These global efforts are designed to develop, evaluate, and deploy cryptographic algorithms that remain safe against both quantum and classical computer attacks, well before fully fault-tolerant quantum systems become available.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Sourcing parts for quantum computers is also very difficult.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Superconducting quantum computers, like those constructed by Google and IBM, need helium-3, a nuclear research byproduct, and special superconducting cables made only by the Japanese company Coax Co.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] On 27 January 2026, the US DARPA agency made a call for proposals for a quantum computing coolant below 1 kelvin, which does not use helium-3.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In February 2026, the Chinese Academy of Sciences announced the testing of a rare-earth alloy, EuCo2Al9, which could fill a similar role.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] One of the greatest challenges involved in constructing quantum computers is controlling or removing quantum decoherence.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] This usually means isolating the system from its environment, as interactions with the external world cause the system to decohere.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] However, other sources of decoherence also exist.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Examples include the quantum gates, the lattice vibrations, and the background thermonuclear spin of the physical system used to implement the qubits.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence is irreversible, as it is effectively non-unitary, and is usually something that should be highly controlled, if not avoided.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence times for candidate systems in particular, the transverse relaxation time *T*2 (for NMR and MRI technology, also called the *dephasing time*), typically range between nanoseconds and seconds at low temperatures.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Currently, some quantum computers require their qubits to be cooled to 20 millikelvin (usually using a dilution refrigerator) in order to prevent significant decoherence.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] A 2020 study argues that ionizing radiation such as cosmic rays can nevertheless cause certain systems to decohere within milliseconds.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As a result, time-consuming tasks may render some quantum algorithms inoperable, as attempting to maintain the state of qubits for a long enough duration will eventually corrupt the superpositions.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] These issues are more difficult for optical approaches as the timescales are orders of magnitude shorter, and an often-cited approach to overcoming them is optical pulse shaping.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Error rates are typically proportional to the ratio of operating time to decoherence time; hence, any operation must be completed much more quickly than the decoherence time.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As described by the threshold theorem, if the error rate is small enough, it is thought to be possible to use quantum error correction to suppress errors and decoherence.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] This allows the total calculation time to be longer than the decoherence time if the error correction scheme can correct errors faster than decoherence introduces them.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] An often-cited figure for the required error rate in each gate for fault-tolerant computation is 10−3, assuming the noise is depolarizing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Meeting this scalability condition is possible for a wide range of systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] However, the use of error correction brings with it the cost of a greatly increased number of required qubits.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The number required to factor integers using Shor's algorithm is still polynomial, and thought to be between L and *L*2, where L is the number of binary digits in the number to be factored; error correction algorithms would inflate this figure by an additional factor of L.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] For a 1000-bit number, this implies a need for about 104 bits without error correction.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] With error correction, the figure would rise to about 107 bits.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Computation time is about *L*2 or about 107 steps and at 1 MHz, about 10 seconds.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] However, the encoding and error-correction overheads increase the size of a real fault-tolerant quantum computer by several orders of magnitude.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Careful estimates show that at least 3 million physical qubits would factor 2,048-bit integer in 5 months on a fully error-corrected trapped-ion quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In terms of the number of physical qubits, to date, this remains the lowest estimate for practically useful integer factorization problem sizing 1,024-bit or larger.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] One approach to overcoming errors combines low-density parity-check code with cat qubits that have intrinsic bit-flip error suppression.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Implementing 100 logical qubits with 768 cat qubits could reduce the error rate to one part in 108 per cycle per bit.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Another approach to the stability-decoherence problem is to create a topological quantum computer with anyons, quasi-particles used as threads, and relying on braid theory to form stable logic gates.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Non-Abelian anyons can, in effect, remember how they have been manipulated, making them potentially useful in quantum computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2025, Microsoft and other organizations are investing in quasi-particle research.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Physicist John Preskill coined the term *quantum supremacy* to describe the engineering feat of demonstrating that a programmable quantum device can solve a problem beyond the capabilities of state-of-the-art classical computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The problem need not be useful, so some view the quantum supremacy test only as a potential future benchmark.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In October 2019, Google AI Quantum, with the help of NASA, became the first to claim to have achieved quantum supremacy by performing calculations on the Sycamore quantum computer more than 3,000,000 times faster than they could be done on Summit, generally considered the world's fastest computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In December 2020, a group at USTC implemented a type of boson sampling on 76 photons with a photonic quantum computer, Jiuzhang, to demonstrate quantum supremacy.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The authors claim that a classical contemporary supercomputer would require a computational time of 600 million years to generate the number of samples their quantum processor can generate in 20 seconds.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Claims of quantum supremacy have generated hype around quantum computing, but they are based on contrived benchmark tasks that do not directly imply useful real-world applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Accordingly, benchmark-level quantum advantage should not be interpreted as proof that quantum computers are already broadly useful across practical computing workloads.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Despite high hopes for quantum computing, significant progress in hardware, and optimism about future applications, a 2023 Nature spotlight article summarized current quantum computers as being "For now, [good for] absolutely nothing".
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The article elaborated that quantum computers are yet to be more useful or efficient than conventional computers in any case, though it also argued that, in the long term, such computers are likely to be useful.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] A 2023 Communications of the ACM article found that current quantum computing algorithms are "insufficient for practical quantum advantage without significant improvements across the software/hardware stack".
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] It argues that the most promising candidates for achieving speedup with quantum computers are "small-data problems", for example, in chemistry and materials science.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] This state of affairs can be traced to several current and long-term considerations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In particular, building computers with large numbers of qubits may be futile if those qubits are not connected well enough and cannot maintain a sufficiently high degree of entanglement for a long time.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] When trying to outperform conventional computers, quantum computing researchers often look for new tasks that can be solved on quantum computers, but this leaves the possibility that efficient non-quantum techniques will be developed in response, as seen for Quantum supremacy demonstrations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Therefore, it is desirable to prove lower bounds on the complexity of best possible non-quantum algorithms (which may be unknown) and show that some quantum algorithms asymptotically improve upon those bounds.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Bill Unruh doubted the practicality of quantum computers in a paper published in 1994.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Paul Davies argued that a 400-qubit computer would even come into conflict with the cosmological information bound implied by the holographic principle.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Skeptics like Gil Kalai doubt that quantum supremacy will ever be achieved.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] continuously variable parameters defining the quantum state of such a system?
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] A practical quantum computer must use a physical system as a programmable quantum register.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Researchers are exploring several technologies as candidates for reliable qubit implementations.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Superconductors and trapped ions are some of the most developed proposals, but experimentalists are considering other hardware possibilities as well.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] For example, topological quantum computer approaches are being explored for more fault-tolerance computing systems.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The first quantum logic gates were implemented with trapped ions and prototype general-purpose machines with up to 20 qubits have been realized.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] However, the technology behind these devices combines complex vacuum equipment, lasers, and microwave and radio frequency equipment, making full-scale processors difficult to integrate with standard computing equipment.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Moreover, the trapped ion system itself has engineering challenges to overcome.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The largest commercial systems are based on superconductor devices and have scaled to 2000 qubits.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] However, the error rates for larger machines have been on the order of 5%.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Technologically, these devices are all cryogenic and scaling to large numbers of qubits requires wafer-scale integration, a serious engineering challenge by itself.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In addition to cryogenic platforms, room-temperature approaches to spin–photon interfaces have been experimentally demonstrated.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Such room-temperature, chip-integrated spin–photon interfaces are being investigated as potential building blocks for heterogeneous quantum networks that combine different qubit modalities and reduce reliance on large cryogenic infrastructures.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Any computational problem solvable by a classical computer is also solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Intuitively, this is because it is believed that all physical phenomena, including the operation of classical computers, can be described using quantum mechanics, which underlies the operation of quantum computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] Conversely, any problem solvable by a quantum computer is also solvable by a classical computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] It is possible to simulate both quantum and classical computers manually with just some paper and a pen, if given enough time.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, any quantum computer can be simulated by a Turing machine.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] In other words, quantum computers provide no additional power over classical computers in terms of computability.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] This means that quantum computers cannot solve undecidable problems like the halting problem, and the existence of quantum computers does not disprove the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] While quantum computers cannot solve any problems that classical computers cannot already solve, it is suspected that they can solve certain problems faster than classical computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, it is known that quantum computers can efficiently factor integers, while this is not believed to be the case for classical computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The class of problems that can be efficiently solved by a quantum computer with bounded error is called BQP, for "bounded error, quantum, polynomial time".
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, BQP is the class of problems that can be solved by a polynomial-time quantum Turing machine with an error probability of at most 1/3.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As a class of probabilistic problems, BQP is the quantum counterpart to BPP ("bounded error, probabilistic, polynomial time"), the class of problems that can be solved by polynomial-time probabilistic Turing machines with bounded error.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] It is known that ${\mathsf {BPP\subseteq BQP}}$ but there is no proof ${\mathsf {BQP\neq BPP}}$ , which intuitively would mean that quantum computers are more powerful than classical computers in terms of time complexity.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] The exact relationship of BQP to P, NP, and PSPACE is not known.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] It is further suspected that BQP is a strict superset of P, meaning that there exist problems that are efficiently solvable by quantum computers that are not efficiently solvable by deterministic classical computers.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be in BQP and are suspected to be outside of P.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] On the relationship of BQP to NP, little is known beyond the fact that some NP problems that are believed not to be in P are also in BQP (integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are both in NP, for example).
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] It is suspected that ${\mathsf {NP\nsubseteq BQP}}$ ; that is, it is believed that there are efficiently checkable problems that are not efficiently solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:ibm-cloud/quantum-computing-p02] As a direct consequence of this belief, it is also suspected that BQP is disjoint from the class of NP-complete problems (if an NP-complete problem were in BQP, then it would follow from NP-hardness that all problems in NP are in BQP).
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The computer system was initially developed to answer questions on the popular quiz show *Jeopardy!* and in 2011, the Watson computer system competed on *Jeopardy!* against champions Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, winning the first-place prize of US$1 million.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In February 2013, IBM announced that Watson's first commercial application would be for utilization management decisions in lung cancer treatment, at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, New York City, in conjunction with WellPoint (now Elevance Health).
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2022, IBM divested and spun-off their Watson Health division into Merative, which was sold to Francisco Partners, an American private equity firm.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The division cost $4 billion to develop but was sold for $1 billion.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] By 2023, Watson resulted in IBM losing 10% of its stock value, costing four times more than what it brought to the company and resulting in mass layoffs.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson was created as a question answering (QA) computing system that IBM built to apply advanced natural language processing, information retrieval, knowledge representation, automated reasoning, and machine learning technologies to the field of open domain question answering.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The system is named DeepQA (though it did not involve the use of deep neural networks).
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In recent years, Watson's capabilities have been extended and the way in which Watson works has been changed to take advantage of new deployment models (Watson on IBM Cloud), evolved machine learning capabilities, and optimized hardware available to developers and researchers.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson uses IBM's DeepQA software and the Apache UIMA (Unstructured Information Management Architecture) framework implementation.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The system was written in various languages, including Java, C++, and Prolog, and runs on the SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 11 operating system using the Apache Hadoop framework to provide distributed computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Other than the DeepQA system, Watson contained several strategy modules.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] For example, one module calculated the amount to bet for *Final Jeopardy*, according to the confidence score on getting the answer right, and the current scores of all contestants.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] One module used the Bayes rule to calculate the probability that each unrevealed question might be the *Daily Double*, using historical data from the J!
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] If a Daily Double is found, the amount to wager is computed by a 2-layered neural network of the same kind as those used by TD-Gammon, a neural network that played backgammon, developed by Gerald Tesauro in the 1990s.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The parameters in the strategy modules were tuned by benchmarking against a statistical model of human contestants fitted on data from the J!
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The system is workload-optimized, integrating massively parallel POWER7 processors and built on IBM's *DeepQA* technology, which it uses to generate hypotheses, gather massive evidence, and analyze data.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson employs a cluster of ninety IBM Power 750 servers, each of which uses a 3.5 GHz POWER7 eight-core processor, with four threads per core.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In total, the system uses 2,880 POWER7 processor threads and 16 terabytes of RAM.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] According to John Rennie, Watson can process 500 gigabytes (the equivalent of a million books) per second.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM master inventor and senior consultant Tony Pearson estimated Watson's hardware cost at about three million dollars.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Its Linpack performance stands at 80 TeraFLOPs, which is about half as fast as the cut-off line for the Top 500 Supercomputers list.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] According to Rennie, all content was stored in Watson's RAM for the Jeopardy game because data stored on hard drives would be too slow to compete with human Jeopardy champions.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The sources of information for Watson include encyclopedias, dictionaries, thesauri, newswire articles and literary works.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson also used databases, taxonomies and ontologies including DBpedia, WordNet and YAGO.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The IBM team provided Watson with millions of documents, including dictionaries, encyclopedias and other reference material, that it could use to build its knowledge.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson parses questions into different keywords and sentence fragments in order to find statistically related phrases.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's main innovation was not in the creation of a new algorithm for this operation, but rather its ability to quickly execute hundreds of proven language analysis algorithms simultaneously.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The more algorithms that find the same answer independently, the more likely Watson is to be correct.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Once Watson has a small number of potential solutions, it is able to check against its database to ascertain whether the solution makes sense or not.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's basic working principle is to parse keywords in a clue while searching for related terms as responses.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] This gives Watson some advantages and disadvantages compared with human *Jeopardy!* players.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson has deficiencies in understanding the context of the clues.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson can read, analyze, and learn from natural language, which gives it the ability to make human-like decisions.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] As a result, human players usually generate responses faster than Watson, especially to short clues.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's programming prevents it from using the popular tactic of buzzing before it is sure of its response.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] However, Watson has consistently better reaction time on the buzzer once it has generated a response, and is immune to human players' psychological tactics, such as jumping between categories on every clue.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In a sequence of 20 mock games of *Jeopardy!*, human participants were able to use the six to seven seconds that Watson needed to hear the clue and decide whether to signal for responding.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] During that time, Watson also has to evaluate the response and determine whether it is sufficiently confident in the result to signal.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Part of the system used to win the *Jeopardy!* contest was the electronic circuitry that receives the "ready" signal and then examines whether Watson's confidence level was great enough to activate the buzzer.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Given the speed of this circuitry compared to the speed of human reaction times, Watson's reaction time was faster than the human contestants except when the human anticipated (instead of reacted to) the ready signal.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] After signaling, Watson speaks with an electronic voice and gives the responses in *Jeopardy!*'s question format.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's voice was synthesized from recordings that actor Jeff Woodman made for an IBM text-to-speech program in 2004.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The *Jeopardy!* staff used different means to notify Watson and the human players when to buzz, which was critical in many rounds.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The humans were notified by a light, which took them tenths of a second to perceive.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson was notified by an electronic signal and could activate the buzzer within about eight milliseconds.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The humans tried to compensate for the perception delay by anticipating the light, but the variation in the anticipation time was generally too great to fall within Watson's response time.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson did not attempt to anticipate the notification signal.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Since Deep Blue's victory over Garry Kasparov in chess in 1997, IBM had been on the hunt for a new challenge.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2004, IBM Research manager Charles Lickel, over dinner with coworkers, noticed that the restaurant they were in had fallen silent.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] He soon discovered the cause of this evening's hiatus: Ken Jennings, who was then in the middle of his successful 74-game run on *Jeopardy!*.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Nearly the entire restaurant had piled toward the televisions, mid-meal, to watch *Jeopardy!*.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Intrigued by the quiz show as a possible challenge for IBM, Lickel passed the idea on, and in 2005, IBM Research executive Paul Horn supported Lickel, pushing for someone in his department to take up the challenge of playing *Jeopardy!* with an IBM system.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Though he initially had trouble finding any research staff willing to take on what looked to be a much more complex challenge than the wordless game of chess, eventually David Ferrucci took him up on the offer.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In competitions managed by the United States government, Watson's predecessor, a system named Piquant, was usually able to respond correctly to only about 35% of clues and often required several minutes to respond.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] To compete successfully on *Jeopardy!*, Watson would need to respond in no more than a few seconds, and at that time, the problems posed by the game show were deemed to be impossible to solve.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In initial tests run during 2006 by David Ferrucci, the senior manager of IBM's Semantic Analysis and Integration department, Watson was given 500 clues from past *Jeopardy!* programs.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] While the best real-life competitors buzzed in half the time and responded correctly to as many as 95% of clues, Watson's first pass could get only about 15% correct.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] During 2007, the IBM team was given three to five years and a staff of 15 people to solve the problems.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Kelly III succeeded Paul Horn as head of IBM Research in 2007.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] *InformationWeek* described Kelly as "the father of Watson" and credited him for encouraging the system to compete against humans on *Jeopardy!*.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] By 2008, the developers had advanced Watson such that it could compete with *Jeopardy!* champions.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] By February 2010, Watson could beat human *Jeopardy!* contestants on a regular basis.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] During the game, Watson had access to 200 million pages of structured and unstructured content consuming four terabytes of disk storage including the full text of the 2011 edition of Wikipedia, but was not connected to the Internet.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] For each clue, Watson's three most probable responses were displayed on the television screen.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson consistently outperformed its human opponents on the game's signaling device, but had trouble in a few categories, notably those having short clues containing only a few words.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Among the team of IBM programmers who worked on Watson was 2001 *Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?* top prize winner Ed Toutant, who himself had appeared on *Jeopardy!* in 1989 (winning one game).
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2008, IBM representatives communicated with *Jeopardy!* executive producer Harry Friedman about the possibility of having Watson compete against Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter, two of the most successful contestants on the show, and the program's producers agreed.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's differences with human players had generated conflicts between IBM and *Jeopardy!* staff during the planning of the competition.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM repeatedly expressed concerns that the show's writers would exploit Watson's cognitive deficiencies when writing the clues, thereby turning the game into a Turing test.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] To alleviate that claim, a third party randomly picked the clues from previously written shows that were never broadcast.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] *Jeopardy!* staff also showed concerns over Watson's reaction time on the buzzer.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Originally Watson signaled electronically, but show staff requested that it press a button physically, as the human contestants would.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Even with a robotic "finger" pressing the buzzer, Watson remained faster than its human competitors.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Ken Jennings noted, "If you're trying to win on the show, the buzzer is all", and that Watson "can knock out a microsecond-precise buzz every single time with little or no variation.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Human reflexes can't compete with computer circuits in this regard." Stephen Baker, a journalist who recorded Watson's development in his book *Final Jeopardy*, reported that the conflict between IBM and *Jeopardy!* became so serious in May 2010 that the competition was almost cancelled.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] As part of the preparation, IBM constructed a mock set in a conference room at one of its technology sites to model the one used on *Jeopardy!*.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Human players, including former *Jeopardy!* contestants, also participated in mock games against Watson with Todd Alan Crain of *The Onion* playing host.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] About 100 test matches were conducted with Watson winning 65% of the games.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] To provide a physical presence in the televised games, Watson was represented by an "avatar" of a globe, inspired by the IBM "smarter planet" symbol.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] A practice match was recorded on January 13, 2011, and the official matches were recorded on January 14, 2011.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] All participants maintained secrecy about the outcome until the match was broadcast in February.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In a practice match before the press on January 13, 2011, Watson won a 15-question round against Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter with a score of $4,400 to Jennings' $3,400 and Rutter's $1,200, though Jennings and Watson were tied before the final $1,000 question.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] None of the three players responded incorrectly to a clue.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The first round was broadcast February 14, 2011, and the second round, on February 15, 2011.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The right to choose the first category had been determined by a draw won by Rutter.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson, represented by a computer monitor display and artificial voice, responded correctly to the second clue and then selected the fourth clue of the first category, a deliberate strategy to find the Daily Double as quickly as possible.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's guess at the Daily Double location was correct.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] At the end of the first round, Watson was tied with Rutter at $5,000; Jennings had $2,000.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's performance was characterized by some quirks.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In one instance, Watson repeated a reworded version of an incorrect response offered by Jennings.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] (Jennings said "What are the '20s?" in reference to the 1920s.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Then Watson said "What is 1920s?") Because Watson could not recognize other contestants' responses, it did not know that Jennings had already given the same response.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In another instance, Watson was initially given credit for a response of "What is a leg?" after Jennings incorrectly responded "What is: he only had one hand?" to a clue about George Eyser (the correct response was, "What is: he's missing a leg?").
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Because Watson, unlike a human, could not have been responding to Jennings' mistake, it was decided that this response was incorrect.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The broadcast version of the episode was edited to omit Trebek's original acceptance of Watson's response.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson also demonstrated complex wagering strategies on the Daily Doubles, with one bet at $6,435 and another at $1,246.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Gerald Tesauro, one of the IBM researchers who worked on Watson, explained that Watson's wagers were based on its confidence level for the category and a complex regression model called the Game State Evaluator.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson took a commanding lead in Double Jeopardy!, correctly responding to both Daily Doubles.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson responded to the second Daily Double correctly with a 32% confidence score.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] However, during the Final Jeopardy! round, Watson was the only contestant to miss the clue in the category U.S.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Cities ("Its largest airport was named for a World War II hero; its second largest, for a World War II battle").
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Rutter and Jennings gave the correct response of Chicago, but Watson's response was "What is Toronto?????" with five question marks indicating a lack of confidence.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Eric Nyberg, a professor at Carnegie Mellon University and a member of the development team, stated that the error occurred because Watson does not possess the comparative knowledge to discard that potential response as not viable.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Although not displayed to the audience as with non-Final Jeopardy! questions, Watson's second choice was Chicago.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Both Toronto and Chicago were well below Watson's confidence threshold, at 14% and 11% respectively.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson wagered only $947 on the question.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The game ended with Jennings with $4,800, Rutter with $10,400, and Watson with $35,734.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] During the introduction, Trebek (a Canadian native) joked that he had learned Toronto was a U.S. city, and Watson's error in the first match prompted an IBM engineer to wear a Toronto Blue Jays jacket to the recording of the second match.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In the first round, Jennings was finally able to choose a Daily Double clue, while Watson responded to one Daily Double clue incorrectly for the first time in the Double Jeopardy!
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] After the first round, Watson placed second for the first time in the competition after Rutter and Jennings were briefly successful in increasing their dollar values before Watson could respond.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Nonetheless, the final result ended with a victory for Watson with a score of $77,147, besting Jennings who scored $24,000 and Rutter who scored $21,600.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The prizes for the competition were $1 million for first place (Watson), $300,000 for second place (Jennings), and $200,000 for third place (Rutter).
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] As promised, IBM donated 100% of Watson's winnings to charity, with 50% of those winnings going to World Vision and 50% going to World Community Grid.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Similarly, Jennings and Rutter donated 50% of their winnings to their respective charities.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In acknowledgement of IBM and Watson's achievements, Jennings made an additional remark in his Final Jeopardy! response: "I for one welcome our new computer overlords", paraphrasing a joke from *The Simpsons*.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Philosopher John Searle argues that Watson—despite impressive capabilities—cannot actually think.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Drawing on his Chinese room thought experiment, Searle claims that Watson, like other computational machines, is capable only of manipulating symbols, but has no ability to understand the meaning of those symbols; however, Searle's experiment has its detractors.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] On February 28, 2011, Watson played an untelevised exhibition match of *Jeopardy!* against members of the United States House of Representatives.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] (D-NJ, a former *Jeopardy!* contestant), who was challenging the computer with Bill Cassidy (R-LA, later Senator from Louisiana), led with Watson in second place.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] However, combining the scores between all matches, the final score was $40,300 for Watson and $30,000 for the congressional players combined.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM's Christopher Padilla said of the match, "The technology behind Watson represents a major advancement in computing.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] After the national press attention gained by the 2011 *Jeopardy!* appearance, IBM sought out partnerships from education to weather and cancer to retail chatbots in order convince business about Watson's alleged capabilities.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] This ultimately led to the failure of Watson to find a profit-making product for the company.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2011, the IBM general counsel wrote in *The National Law Review* arguing that the law profession will become more efficient and better with Watson.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] After the national attention *Jeopardy!* afforded them, began an ultimately unsuccessful and expensive project that began when the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center tried to use Watson to help doctors diagnose and treat cancer patients.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Ultimately, the division cost $4 billion to develop but was sold for a quarter of that—$1 billion, in 2022.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] — Mac Schwerin, "America Forgot About IBM Watson.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In the end, IBM's initial vision for Watson as a transformative technology capable of revolutionizing industries did not materialize as anticipated.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's capabilities were primarily suited to specific tasks, like natural language processing for trivia games, rather than generalized commercial problem-solving.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson's mismatch between capabilities and IBM's marketing contributed significantly to Watson's commercial struggles and eventual decline.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The overstated claims about Watson's abilities also caused public sentiment to turn against the idea of Watson and artificial intelligence.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Between 2019 and 2023, IBM shifted focus to a separate initiative WatsonX, distinctly different from Watson, aiming for narrower, industry-targeted technology within IBM's cloud computing and platform-based strategies IBM Watsonx.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM's Watson was used to analyze medical datasets to provide physicians with guidance on diagnoses and cancer treatment decisions.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] When a physician submitted a query to Watson, the system started a multi-step process by parsing the input to identify key information, examining patient data to uncover relevant medical and hereditary history, and finally compare various data sources to form and test hypotheses.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM claimed that Watson's could draw from a wide range of sources, including treatment guidelines, electronic medical records, and research materials.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Although, company executives would later blame the lack of data on the projects ultimate failure.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Notably, Watson has not been involved in the actual diagnosis process, but rather assists doctors in identifying suitable treatment options for patients who have already been diagnosed.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In fact, a study of 1,000 challenging patient cases found that Watson's recommendations matched those of human doctors in an impressive 99% of cases.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM established partnerships with the Cleveland Clinic, the MD Anderson Cancer Center, and Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center to further its mission in healthcare.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2011, IBM entered into a research partnership with Nuance Communications and physicians at the University of Maryland and Harvard to develop a commercial product using Watson's clinical decision support capabilities.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM partnered with WellPoint (now Anthem) in 2011 to utilize Watson in suggesting treatment options to physicians, and in 2013, Watson was deployed in its first commercial application for utilization management decisions in lung cancer treatment at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The Cleveland Clinic collaboration aimed to enhance Watson's health expertise and support medical professionals in treating patients more effectively.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] However, the MD Anderson Cancer Center pilot program, initiated in 2013, ultimately failed to meet its goals and was discontinued after $65 million in investment.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2016, IBM launched "IBM Watson for Oncology", a product designed to provide personalized, evidence-based cancer care options to physicians and patients.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] This initiative marked a significant milestone in the adoption of Watson's technology in the healthcare industry.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Additionally, IBM partnered with Manipal Hospitals in India to offer Watson's expertise to patients online.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The company ultimately faced challenges in the healthcare market, with no profit and increased competition.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2022, IBM announced the sell-off of its Watson Health unit to Francisco Partners, marking a significant shift in the company's approach to the healthcare industry.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] On January 9, 2014, IBM announced it was creating a business unit around Watson.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM Watson Group will have headquarters in New York City's Silicon Alley and will employ 2,000 people.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM has invested $1 billion to get the division going.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] Watson Group will develop three new cloud-delivered services: Watson Discovery Advisor, Watson Engagement Advisor, and Watson Explorer.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] The company is also launching a $100 million venture fund to spur application development for "cognitive" applications.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] According to IBM, the cloud-delivered enterprise-ready Watson has seen its speed increase 24 times over—a 2,300 percent improvement in performance and its physical size shrank by 90 percent—from the size of a master bedroom to three stacked pizza boxes.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM CEO Virginia Rometty said she wants Watson to generate $10 billion in annual revenue within ten years.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] In 2017, IBM and MIT established a new joint research venture in artificial intelligence.
[src:ibm-cloud/watson-computer] IBM invested $240 million to create the MIT–IBM Watson AI Lab in partnership with MIT, which brings together researchers in academia and industry to advance AI research, with projects ranging from computer vision and NLP to devising new ways to ensure that AI systems are fair, reliable and secure.
